ğŸŸ© Problem

You need to check if an expression contains redundant brackets.  
A bracket pair is redundant when nothing meaningful (no operator) exists inside it.  
Example:  
(a) â†’ redundant  
((a + b)) â†’ outer pair redundant  
(a + (b + c)) â†’ all meaningful, no redundant brackets

ğŸŸ© Sample Input
3
(a + b)
((a + b))
(a + (b + c))

ğŸŸ© Sample Output
No
Yes
No

ğŸŸ© Approach
- Use a stack.  
- When you see ')', pop everything until '(' and check whether any operator appeared.  
- If no operator appeared between the pair, the brackets were redundant.


ğŸŸ© Solution (Manual Stack)

import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        int n = sc.nextInt();
        sc.nextLine();

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            String s = sc.nextLine().trim();
            char[] stack = new char[s.length()];
            int top = -1;

            boolean extra = false;

            for (int j = 0; j < s.length(); j++) {
                char ch = s.charAt(j);
                if (ch != ')') {
                    stack[++top] = ch;
                } 
                else {
                    char t = stack[top--];
                    boolean hasOperator = false;
                    while (t != '(') {
                        if (t == '+' || t == '-' || t == '*' || t == '/') {
                            hasOperator = true;
                        }
                        t = stack[top--];
                    }
                    if (hasOperator == false) {
                        extra = true;
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }
            System.out.println(extra ? "Yes" : "No");
        }
    }
}


ğŸŸ© Time Complexity - O(n) per expression â€” each character pushed and popped once
ğŸŸ© Space Complexity - O(n) â€” stack holds up to the full expression
